# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carbon-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carbon-lang/carbon-programming-language] The language intends to fix several perceived shortcomings of C++ but otherwise provides a similar feature set.
[src:carbon-lang/carbon-programming-language] The main goals of the language are readability and "bi-directional interoperability" (which allows the user to include C++ code in the Carbon file), as opposed to using a new language like Rust, that, whilst being influenced by C++, is not two-way compatible with C++ programs.
[src:carbon-lang/carbon-programming-language] Changes to the language will be decided by the Carbon leads.
[src:carbon-lang/carbon-programming-language] It aims to build on top of the C++ ecosystem the way in an analogous role to TypeScript to JavaScript, or Kotlin to Java.
[src:carbon-lang/carbon-programming-language] Carbon's documents, design, implementation, and related tools are hosted on GitHub under the Apache-2.0 license with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:carbon-lang/compiled-language] Informally, a **compiled language** is a programming language that is usually implemented with a compiler rather than an interpreter.
[src:carbon-lang/compiled-language] Because any language can theoretically be either compiled or interpreted, the term lacks clarity: compilation and interpretation are properties of a programming language implementation, not of a programming language.
[src:carbon-lang/compiled-language] Some languages have both compilers and interpreters.
[src:carbon-lang/compiled-language] Furthermore, a single implementation can involve both a compiler and an interpreter.
[src:carbon-lang/compiled-language] For example, in some environments, source code is first compiled to an intermediate form (e.g., bytecode), which is then interpreted by an application virtual machine.
[src:carbon-lang/compiled-language] In other environments, a just-in-time compiler selectively compiles some code at runtime, blurring the distinction further.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Systems programming requires a great degree of hardware awareness.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Its goal is to achieve efficient use of available resources, either because the software itself is performance-critical or because even small efficiency improvements directly transform into significant savings of time or money.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] In systems programming, often limited programming facilities are available.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] The use of automatic garbage collection is not common and debugging is sometimes hard to do.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] The runtime library, if available at all, is usually far less powerful, and does less error checking.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Because of those limitations, monitoring and logging are often used; operating systems may have extremely elaborate logging subsystems.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Implementing certain parts in operating systems and networking requires systems programming, for example implementing paging (virtual memory) or a device driver for an operating system.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Originally systems programmers invariably wrote in assembly language.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Experiments with hardware support in high level languages in the late 1960s led to such languages as PL/S, BLISS, BCPL, and extended ALGOL for Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Forth also has applications as a systems language.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] In the 1970s, C became widespread, aided by the growth of Unix.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] More recently a subset of C++ called Embedded C++ has seen some use, for instance it is used in the I/O Kit drivers of macOS.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Engineers working at Google created Go in 2007 to address developer productivity in large distributed systems, with developer-focused features such as Concurrency, Garbage Collection, and faster program compilation than C and C++.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] In 2015 Rust came out, a general-purpose programming language often used in systems programming.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Rust was designed with memory safety in mind and to be as performant as C and C++.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] For historical reasons, some organizations use the term *systems programmer* to describe a job function which would be more accurately termed systems administrator.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] This is particularly true in organizations whose computer resources have historically been dominated by mainframes, although the term is even used to describe job functions which do not involve mainframes.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] This usage arose because administration of IBM mainframes often involved the writing of custom assembler code (IBM's Basic Assembly Language (BAL)), which integrated with the operating system such as OS/MVS, DOS/VSE or VM/CMS.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] Indeed, some IBM software products had substantial code contributions from customer programming staff.
[src:carbon-lang/systems-programming] This type of programming is progressively less common, and increasingly done in C rather than Assembly, but the term *systems programmer* is still used as the de-facto job title for staff administering IBM mainframes even in cases where they do not regularly engage in systems programming activities.
